    <div class="insideleft"><div class="insideright"><div class="inside">
		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="2">
          <tr>
            <td width="65"><img src="/_templates/orangeads/images/q.jpg" />&nbsp;</td>
            <td align="left" valign="middle"><h3>Trading Equity Options And Capital Gains Tax Rates?</h3></td>
          </tr>
        </table>
		<p class="postmetadata">Question by peter p | Posted in Investing</p>
					<p style="font-weight: bold;"> is there anything noteworthy to know about capital gains tax rates when it comes to speculating in options....or are any gains taxed at regular be-term capital gains tax rates (ie; ~35% as my regular equity trades are taxed)<br />
<br />
many thanks<br />
</p>
							<hr>
			<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			  <tr>
			    <td><strong>Answer:</strong> Privilege trades are usually taxed as short term capital gains (even LEAPS held for over a year), regardless of the hanker or short position.  However, if you write a call against stock that you have already held long term, then the choice premium is long term if you are assigned on the call.  There may be other exceptions that I am not aware of.  I do most of my option trading as over writes or buy-writes in my IRA or Roth, so taxes are not of regard.</td>
		      </tr>
		  </table>
			
                                                                       
